05172nam a22006615i 9780822384571DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20032003ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223845717 a10.1515/97808223845712doi  a(DE-B1597)553512  a(OCoLC)1229160875  a(OCoLC)1167482792  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPS228.L47bK46 2003 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a813/.509352066431 aKent, Kathryn R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMaking Girls into Women :bAmerican Women's Writing and the Rise of Lesbian Identity /cKathryn R. Kent; Eve Kosofsky Sedgwick, Michael Moon, Jonathan Goldberg, Michèle Aina Barale. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b3 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSeries Q00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1. "SINGLE WHITE FEMALE": THE SEXUAL POLITICS OF SPINSTERHOOD IN HARRIET BEECHER STOWE'S OLDTOWN FOLKS -- t2. "TRYING ALL KINDS": LOUISA MAY ALCOTT'S PEDAGOGIC EROTICS -- t3. "SCOUTING FOR GIRLS": READING AND RECRUITMENT -- t4. "EXCREATE A NO SENSE": THE EROTIC CURRENCY OF GERTRUDE STEIN'S TENDER BUTTONS -- t5. THE M MULTIPLYING: MARIANNE MOORE, ELIZABETH BISHOP, AND THE PLEASURES OF INFLUENCE, PART 1 -- t6. INFLUENCE AND INVITATION: MARIANNE MOORE, ELIZABETH BISHOP, AND THE PLEASURES OF INFLUENCE, PART 2 -- tCONCLUSION -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMaking Girls into Women offers an account of the historical emergence of "the lesbian" by looking at late-nineteenth- and early-twentieth-century women's writing. Kathryn R. Kent proposes that modern lesbian identity in the United States has its roots not just, or even primarily, in sexology and medical literature, but in white, middle-class women's culture. Kent demonstrates how, as white women's culture shifted more and more from the home to the school, workplace, and boarding house, the boundaries between the public and private spheres began to dissolve. She shows how, within such spaces, women's culture, in attempting to mold girls into proper female citizens, ended up inciting in them other, less normative, desires and identifications, including ones Kent calls "protolesbian" or queer.Kent not only analyzes how texts represent queer erotics, but also theorizes how texts might produce them in readers. She describes the ways postbellum sentimental literature such as that written by Harriet Beecher Stowe, Louisa May Alcott, and Emma D. Kelley eroticizes, reacts against, and even, in its own efforts to shape girls' selves, contributes to the production of queer female identifications and identities. Tracing how these identifications are engaged and critiqued in the early twentieth century, she considers works by Djuna Barnes, Gertrude Stein, Marianne Moore, and Elizabeth Bishop, as well as in the queer subject-forming effects of another modern invention, the Girl Scouts. Making Girls into Women ultimately reveals that modern lesbian identity marks an extension of, rather than a break from, nineteenth-century women's culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aAmerican literaturexWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aGirls in literature. 0aLesbians in literature. 0aLesbians' writings, AmericanxHistory and criticism. 0aWomen in literature. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBarale, Michèle Aina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGoldberg, Jonathan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMoon, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSedg